Git stuff



Add a new remote repo
 - git remote add <name> <url> (e.g., git remote add sok https://github.com/SOK-KDHE/ksTracking.git)



Link a local folder to a remote GitHub repo via git bash
 - Create new repo in GitHub
 - Open git bash shell
 - cd my_folder
 - git init
 - git add .
 - git commit - "A commit message"
 - git remote add origin https://github.com/eliotmonaco/my_repo.git
 - git remote -v (to verify)
 - git push origin main
(https://docs.github.com/en/migrations/importing-source-code/using-the-command-line-to-import-source-code/adding-locally-hosted-code-to-github)



Amend the last commit after changes were pushed to remote
 - git add .
 - git commit --amend
 - (Text editor will open where the commit message can be changed)
 - git push --force



Git workflow for package
 - git checkout develop
 - (Do whatever work)
 - git add . [OR] --all         Stage all modified files
 - git commit -m "[message]"    Commit staged files
 - git push origin develop      Push local branch to GitHub
 - git checkout main
 - git merge develop            Merge develop with main (local)
 - git push                     Push main to origin
 - git checkout develop



Some git commands
 - git branch [name]            Create new branch
 - git branch -d [name]         Delete local branch
 - git push origin -d [name]    Delete remote branch
 - git fetch --prune
    - Do this if RStudio still shows a branch that was deleted. It will update the local Git repository with the latest changes from the remote repository and remove any references to deleted branches.



PAT stuff
 - Happy Git with R recommends these scopes:
 - gitcreds::gitcreds_set(url = "https://github.com/SOK-KDHE")
 - gitcreds::gitcreds_get(url = "https://github.com/SOK-KDHE")
